java.util.Date: Represents a point in time with both date and time components. It is mutable, not thread-safe, and has limited functionality. It is outdated and not recommended for new development.

java.time.Instant: Represents an instantaneous point on the timeline, usually in UTC. It is immutable, thread-safe, and provides methods for comparing and manipulating timestamps. It is suitable for machine-readable timestamps.

java.util.Calendar: Represents a calendar with date and time components. It is mutable, not thread-safe, and has complex APIs. Its usage is discouraged in favor of the newer java.time API.

java.time.LocalDateTime: Represents a date and time without time zone information. It is immutable, thread-safe, and provides methods for working with dates, times, and durations. It is suitable for most date and time operations.